<subSubSection lastPageId="48" lastPageNumber="49" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="47.[151,1437,798,1003]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,266,798,823]" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: Large jird with soft, dense fur. Fur color pale sandy dorsally, underside pure white, line of demarcation not very distinct. Ears small and not pigmented, claws white or pale (
<figureCitation box="[922,1036,834,859]" captionStart="FIGURE 53" captionStartId="47.[151,250,1825,1847]" captionTargetBox="[226,1360,1055,1803]" captionTargetId="figure@47.[226,1360,1055,1803]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="FIGURE 53. Sundevall's jird, Meriones crassus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202881/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Figure 53</figureCitation>
). Hind feet covered with white hair. Tail terminates with a black brush (not as well developed as in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomas" authorityYear="1919" box="[859,976,870,895]" class="Mammalia" family="Muridae" genus="Meriones" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="47" pageNumber="48" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="libycus">
<emphasis box="[859,976,870,895]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">M. libycus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Tail length is about equal to head body length. Skull robust, with extremely large bullae that extend quite beyond the supraoccipital. Braincase broad. The suprameatal triangle of bullae large and widely open at its posterior end. Upper incisors with anterior median groove (
<figureCitation box="[243,357,978,1003]" captionStart="FIGURE 54" captionStartId="48.[151,250,1997,2019]" captionTargetBox="[264,1323,735,1975]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[264,1323,735,1975]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURE 54 A. Dorsal, B. Ventral, C. Lateral views of the skull, and D. Upper maxillary teeth for Meriones crassus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1202883/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="48">Figure 54</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
